@page "/item/new"

@* THE PRECEDENCE WITNESS. `/item/new` and `/item/{Id:int}` both have two segments and both could be
   asked to match `/item/new`; Blazor picks this one, because a LITERAL segment is more specific than a
   parameter -- and it picks it regardless of which page was declared first.

   The emitted router is a linear scan, so the compiler sorts the table by ASP.NET Core's own precedence
   digits before emitting it. That is why this page needs no ordering hint of its own, and why the
   ranking costs zero bytes on the wire (decision 163). *@
<div id="page"><h2 id="where">new</h2><a id="to-home" href="/">home</a></div>
